  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Quality Education Programme in Republic of Congo</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">With a lack of teacher training and very low pay for teachers, it can be hard for children in the Republic of Congo to get a good education. There&apos;&apos;s no role for children in decision making or expressing their ideas for improving schools, or in making a better environment. School governance is often ineffective with very little parental involvement, and support for disabled children is virtually non-existent. Africa Future Development is working to raise the quality of primary and secondary education and widen access to schools in the Republic of Congo. They&apos;&apos;re working with local organisations and educational professionals, to promote effective teaching and to encourage the participation of parents and children in dozens of rural schools. As a result of the project, pupils, teachers and parents are more involved in decision making to improve teaching practice and school facilities. Teachers are also being trained in the special educational needs of children with disabilities to enable them to attend their local schools. In addition to the project grant, Africa Future Development has been awarded &#xA3;18,500 to help strengthen the organisation and their work, enabling them to support their local partners in Africa to continue to provide effective solutions to the issues they address.</narrative>
  </description>
